        Chart Update 25/08/2023

        A lot of things have happened this week to little old me. Firstly, I got my GCSE results, and I can officially rule myself out of ever becoming a scientist in my lifetime, without hoping for a freak accident. Second, I'm on holiday in Cornwall, so to commemorate how rushed this review is, I will try to do it in rhyming couplets.

        Ladies and gentleman, stop what you're doing. The charts are exciting, so start with your wooing. The Barbie songs may be old, but by golly they are lasting. And with a change at the top, the results are quite chastening. Everyone's secret crush, Dua Lipa herself, has now claimed a fourth chart-topper to make us feel elf (Excited Like Fudge).Dance The Nighthas done it, and I for one am glad. 'Cause as far as I'm concerned, her not being there would make me mad. Two of her best-sellers were duets, which is a little worrying, but now's not the time for that, because the sales they are hurrying. So congrats to young Dua, and her legions of fans. And the people at Warner Bros., whose brains will be frying like pans.

        The new hits, sadly, are hard to come by, so I might as well run down some climbers to make us look wry. No one look any further than Doja, the Cat who can make magic out of a hat, and with her eleven-place jump, safe to sayPaint The Town Redain't tat. Less positive, however, is the unmemorable cass, who should be lucky he's not been sued yet, his success is so "Picasso".Prada'sup twelve, and I am not happy, but there are other stuff here that makes me go snappy. For instance,Dog Days Are Over, which I may love to bits, but is only here 'cause Guardians 3 did things, which makes my emotions the pits. And one of the two exits from the tenners, is Olivia Rodrigo, which isn't very "zenners" (look, something had to rhyme, ok?). And Rudimental come back, for no other reason, than to make me feel depressed, whenever the season.

        The album chart sees Hozier make his mark on the world, as his album I forgot the name of, turns the album market swirled. His singles impact, however, is somewhat of a mix, with his best showing down at 86. Jazzy keeps climbing, and so does Prinz, which causes me to lament, and contemplate putting this review in the bins.

        Also new here are Giggs and Billy Gillies, but now for a song that gives me the chillies. For those who don't know the tale of this next song, oh boy, WE WILL BE HERE ALL DAY LONG.North Men North Of Richmondis a pretty average song, for starters, even though we barely get ANY folk in the charters. And I'm sure that Oliver Anthony Music is a nice guy in person, but this song makes him appealling as Paul Merson (weird metaphor, but whatever). Being labelled a "right-wing anthem" certainly doesn't help, and it rising 41 places is also somewhat of a yelp. Let's just hope it disappears quickly, before my taste for this song goes rapidly sickly.

        But yeah, that's that, enjoy the show. I'll be back next time, away I go!


        (P.S. Sadly, this review coincides with the return of everybody's least favourite commenter, Frank Griffin, who went from just your average guy, to the most insufferable human being in the 2020s. This is his first time reporting in this modern era. Just making sure you're aware of his presence, in case he blackmails us into thinking that O-Rod's new found love of guitar isn't okily-dokily.)

        I am worried that him being decried as a right-winger and ostracised could result in him finding his home in that crowd, who are certainly very interested in claiming him. Clearly many of his complaints resonate with working-class folk in the US and here too. As leftists, I feel we have to meet him where he is at. Not everyone who uses right-wing talking points is a fascist who can't be reasoned with. Billy Bragg seemed to understand this when he made his pro-union response song.

        I said on the midweek charts page that it's moreso a conservative anthem due to who is listening to it, rather than the content of the song. There is a clear individualist streak running through the song though. I mean, if there wasn't, conservatives wouldn't be interested and no one would know who this guy is. Kinda sad really. In any case, we'll have to keep an eye on where this guy goes from here and how his politics evolves.

        Given, however, the fact that the same mechanism that propelled this tune into the upper echelons of the charts also propelled Jason Aldean's song, there is probably reason to be concerned about the greater cultural context, aside from the song or Oliver Anthony himself. So you definitely have good reason to be skeptical. That being said, the unprecedented insignificance of downloads as a form of music consumption contrasted with the influence they have in determining chart positions perhaps makes it look like there's a bigger paradigm shift than there really is. That's not to say that these songs don't do decent numbers on streaming, though.

        In lighter news, I did note that country musician Tyler Childers did notch his first ever US chart entry with his song "In Your Love", whose video tells the story of two gay coal miners in the 1950s in Childers' native Kentucky. I think it's often the case that controversy breeds attention. For leftists, the important thing is to reframe the narrative of the culture wars so that working class solidarity straddles lines of race, sexuality, gender identity, etc., while remaining very much aware of the systemic injustices that minority groups face, and appealing to the compassion in all of us to resolve them. Notably, in a video addendum to his traditional fiddle album Long Violent History, whose title track discusses systemic racial injustice, Childers appealed to his white rural listeners to have sympathy with BLM protesters in the face of police brutality. He noted that the very same institutions responsible for the oppression of Black folk, are also responsible for the oppression of many white rural folk who can't seem to get ahead. I think that's the message we have to take forward.
